03:40.680 --> 03:45.600
 And now, here's my conversation with Donald Knuth.

03:45.600 --> 03:55.040
 In 1957, at Case Tech, you were once allowed to spend several evenings with an IBM 650

03:55.040 --> 03:59.440
 computer, as you've talked about in the past, and you fell in love with computing then.

03:59.440 --> 04:06.520
 Can you take me back to that moment with the IBM 650?

04:06.520 --> 04:09.240
 What was it that grabbed you about that computer?

04:09.240 --> 04:19.480
 So the IBM 650 was this machine that, well, it didn't fill a room, but it was big and

04:19.480 --> 04:20.480
 noisy.

04:20.480 --> 04:24.200
 But when I first saw it, it was through a window, and there were just a lot of lights

04:24.200 --> 04:26.520
 flashing on it.

04:26.520 --> 04:36.080
 And I was a freshman, I had a job with the statistics group, and I was supposed to punch

04:36.080 --> 04:40.440
 cards for data and then sort them on another machine.

04:40.440 --> 04:48.440
 But then they got this new computer, came in, and it had interesting lights, okay.

04:48.440 --> 04:54.120
 So, well, but I had a key to the building, so I could get in and look at it and got a

04:54.120 --> 04:56.200
 manual for it.

04:56.200 --> 05:00.480
 And my first experience was based on the fact that I could punch cards, basically, which

05:00.480 --> 05:02.520
 was a big thing for the IBM 650.

05:02.520 --> 05:13.600
 But the IBM 650 was big in size, but incredibly small in power in memory.

05:13.600 --> 05:20.440
 It had 2,000 words of memory, and a word of memory was 10 decimal digits plus a sign.

05:20.440 --> 05:26.880
 And it would do, add two numbers together, you could probably expect that would take,

05:26.880 --> 05:30.280
 I'll say, three milliseconds.

05:30.280 --> 05:31.280
 So...

05:31.280 --> 05:34.720
 Yes, the memory is the constraint, the memory is the problem.

05:34.720 --> 05:39.080
 That was why it took three milliseconds, because it took five milliseconds for the drum to

05:39.080 --> 05:45.480
 go around, and you had to wait, I don't know, five cycle times.

05:45.480 --> 05:50.120
 If you have an instruction in one position on the drum, then it would be ready to read

05:50.120 --> 05:55.720
 the data for the instruction, and you know, go three notches.

05:55.720 --> 06:00.760
 The drum is 50 cycles around, and you go three cycles, and you can get the data, and then

06:00.760 --> 06:04.600
 you can go another three cycles and get to your next instruction.

06:04.600 --> 06:10.000
 If the instruction is there, otherwise you spin until you get to the right place.

06:10.000 --> 06:14.160
 And we had no random access memory whatsoever until my senior year.

06:14.160 --> 06:19.840
 In senior year, we got 50 words of random access memory, which were priceless, and we

06:19.840 --> 06:27.640
 would move stuff up to the random access memory in 60 word chunks, and then we would start

06:27.640 --> 06:28.640
 again.

06:28.640 --> 06:31.200
 So, subroutine went to go up there and...

06:31.200 --> 06:37.760
 Could you have predicted the future 60 years later of computing from then?

06:37.760 --> 06:44.360
 You know, in fact, the hardest question I was ever asked was, what could I have predicted?

06:44.360 --> 06:50.400
 In other words, the interviewer asked me, she said, you know, what about computing has

06:50.400 --> 06:54.680
 surprised you, you know, and immediately I ran, I rattled off a couple dozen things,

06:54.680 --> 06:57.600
 and then she said, okay, so what didn't surprise?

06:57.600 --> 07:05.600
 And I tried for five minutes to think of something that I would have predicted, and I couldn't.

07:05.600 --> 07:12.240
 But let me say that this machine, I didn't know, well, there wasn't much else in the

07:12.240 --> 07:13.520
 world at that time.

07:13.520 --> 07:19.640
 The 650 was the first machine that was, that there were more than a thousand of ever.

07:19.640 --> 07:25.200
 Before that, there were, you know, each machine there might be a half a dozen examples, maybe

07:25.200 --> 07:26.200
 a couple dozen.

07:26.200 --> 07:28.160
 Maybe a couple dozen mass produced.

07:28.160 --> 07:37.920
 The first one, yeah, done in quantity, and IBM didn't sell them, they rented them, but

07:37.920 --> 07:44.760
 they rented them to universities at great, you know, had a great deal.

07:44.760 --> 07:51.680
 And so that's why a lot of students learned about computers at that time.

07:51.680 --> 07:58.520
 So you refer to people, including yourself, who gravitate toward a kind of computational

07:58.520 --> 08:00.920
 thinking as geeks.

08:00.920 --> 08:02.920
 At least I've heard you use that terminology.

08:02.920 --> 08:08.240
 It's true that I think there's something that happened to me as I was growing up that

08:08.240 --> 08:14.160
 made my brain structure in a certain way that resonates with computers.

08:14.160 --> 08:20.040
 So there's this space of people, two percent of the population you empirically estimate.

08:20.040 --> 08:27.960
 That's been fairly constant over most of my career, however, it might be different now

08:27.960 --> 08:30.880
 because kids have different experiences when they're young.

08:30.880 --> 08:35.560
 So what does the world look like to a geek?

08:35.560 --> 08:45.440
 What is, what is this aspect of thinking that is unique to, yeah, that makes a geek?

08:45.440 --> 08:49.400
 This is a hugely important question.

08:49.400 --> 08:59.600
 In the 50s, IBM noticed that there were geeks and nongeeks, and so they tried to hire geeks

08:59.600 --> 09:03.860
 and they put out ads with papers saying, you know, if you play chess, come to Madison

09:03.860 --> 09:08.100
 Avenue for an interview or something like this, they were trying for some things.

09:08.100 --> 09:15.000
 So what is it that I find easy and other people tend to find harder?

09:15.000 --> 09:17.760
 And I think there's two main things.

09:17.760 --> 09:26.960
 One is the ability to jump levels of abstraction.

09:26.960 --> 09:33.840
 So you see something in the large and you see something in the small and you pass between

09:33.840 --> 09:35.880
 those unconsciously.

09:35.880 --> 09:43.720
 So you know that in order to solve some big problem, what you need to do is add one to

09:43.720 --> 09:50.240
 a certain register and it gets to another step and below the, I mean, I don't go down

09:50.240 --> 09:55.240
 to the electron level, but I knew what those milliseconds were, what the drum was like.

09:55.240 --> 10:01.880
 On the 650, I knew how I was going to factor a number or find a root of an equation or

10:01.880 --> 10:05.080
 something because of what was doing.

10:05.080 --> 10:11.120
 And as I'm debugging, I'm going through, you know, did I make a key punch error?

10:11.120 --> 10:13.080
 Did I write the wrong instruction?

10:13.080 --> 10:16.040
 Do I have the wrong thing in a register?

10:16.040 --> 10:26.920
 And each level is different and this idea of being able to see something at lots of

10:26.920 --> 10:32.800
 levels and fluently go between them seems to me to be more pronounced, much more pronounced

10:32.800 --> 10:37.480
 in the people that resonate with computers.

10:37.480 --> 10:47.520
 So in my books, I also don't stick just to the high level, but I mix low level stuff

10:47.520 --> 10:55.720
 with high level and this means that some people think, you know, that I should write better

10:55.720 --> 11:04.120
 books and it's probably true, but other people say, well, if you think like that, then that's

11:04.120 --> 11:10.040
 the way to train yourself, keep mixing the levels and learn more and more how to jump

11:10.040 --> 11:11.040
 between.

11:11.040 --> 11:12.040
 So that's the one thing.

11:12.040 --> 11:21.880
 The other thing is that it's more of a talent to be able to deal with non uniformity where

11:21.880 --> 11:30.200
 there's case one, case two, case three, instead of having one or two rules that govern everything.

11:30.200 --> 11:38.600
 So it doesn't bother me if I need, like an algorithm has 10 steps to it, you know, each

11:38.600 --> 11:44.360
 step does something else that doesn't bother me, but a lot of pure mathematics is based

11:44.360 --> 11:48.800
 on one or two rules, which are universal.

11:48.800 --> 11:54.080
 And so this means that people like me sometimes work with systems that are more complicated

11:54.080 --> 12:01.400
 than necessary because it doesn't bother us that we don't, that we didn't figure out the

12:01.400 --> 12:02.400
 simple rule.

12:02.400 --> 12:07.520
 And you mentioned that while Jacobi Bool, Abel, all the mathematicians in the 19th century

12:07.520 --> 12:15.960
 may have had symptoms of geek, the first 100% legit geek was touring Alan Turing.

12:15.960 --> 12:25.800
 I think he had a lot more of this quality than any, just from reading the kind of stuff

12:25.800 --> 12:26.800
 he did.

12:26.800 --> 12:34.480
 So how does touring, what influence has touring had on you in your way of thinking?

12:34.480 --> 12:35.480
 Well, okay.

12:35.480 --> 12:40.520
 So I didn't know that aspect of him until after I graduated somewhere.

12:40.520 --> 12:47.880
 As an undergraduate, we had a class that talked about computability theory and touring machines.

12:47.880 --> 12:56.520
 And it was all, it sounded like a very specific kind of purely theoretical approach to stuff.

12:56.520 --> 13:08.560
 So how old was he when I learned that he had a design machine and that he wrote a wonderful

13:08.560 --> 13:13.800
 manual for Manchester machines.

13:13.800 --> 13:23.960
 And he invented subroutines and he was a real hacker that he had his hands dirty.

13:23.960 --> 13:30.840
 I thought for many years that he had only done purely formal work.

13:30.840 --> 13:38.400
 As they started reading his own publications, I could feel this kinship.

13:38.400 --> 13:46.160
 And of course, he had a lot of peculiarities, like he wrote numbers backwards because left

13:46.160 --> 13:51.160
 to right instead of right to left, because that was easier for computers to process them

13:51.160 --> 13:52.160
 that way.

13:52.160 --> 13:54.360
 What do you mean left to right?

13:54.360 --> 14:03.680
 He would write Pi as 9514.3, I mean, okay.

14:03.680 --> 14:07.120
 Right, got it.

14:07.120 --> 14:17.960
 On the blackboard, I mean, he had trained himself to do that because the computers he

14:17.960 --> 14:21.160
 was working with worked that way inside.

14:21.160 --> 14:22.560
 Trained himself to think like a computer.

14:22.560 --> 14:23.560
 Well, there you go.

14:23.560 --> 14:26.720
 That's geek thinking.

14:26.720 --> 14:32.280
 You've practiced some of the most elegant formalism in computer science.

14:32.280 --> 14:38.200
 And yet you're the creator of a concept like literate programming, which seems to move

14:38.200 --> 14:42.920
 closer to natural language type of description of programming.

14:42.920 --> 14:43.920
 Yeah, absolutely.

14:43.920 --> 14:50.920
 Do you see those two as conflicting as the formalism of theory and the idea of literate

14:50.920 --> 14:51.920
 programming?

14:51.920 --> 14:59.080
 So there we are in a nonuniform system where I don't think one size fits all and I don't

14:59.080 --> 15:03.360
 think all truth lies in one kind of expertise.

15:03.360 --> 15:13.640
 And so somehow, in a way, you'd say my life is a convex combination of English and mathematics.

15:13.640 --> 15:14.800
 And you're okay with that?

15:14.800 --> 15:16.240
 And not only that, I think...

15:16.240 --> 15:17.240
 Thrive in it.

15:17.240 --> 15:18.240
 I wish...

15:18.240 --> 15:19.240
 I want my kids to be that way.

15:19.240 --> 15:20.240
 I want...

15:20.240 --> 15:21.240
 Et cetera.

15:21.240 --> 15:25.480
 Use left brain, right brain at the same time, you got a lot more done.

15:25.480 --> 15:28.960
 That was part of the bargain.

15:28.960 --> 15:36.680
 And I've heard that you didn't really read for pleasure until into your 30s in literature.

15:36.680 --> 15:37.920
 Yeah, that's true.

15:37.920 --> 15:41.680
 You know more about me than I do, but I'll try to be consistent with what you read.

15:41.680 --> 15:43.080
 Yeah, no, just believe me.

15:43.080 --> 15:45.680
 I just go with whatever story I tell you.

15:45.680 --> 15:46.840
 It would be easier that way.

15:46.840 --> 15:47.840
 The conversation...

15:47.840 --> 15:49.320
 Right, yeah, no, that's true.

15:49.320 --> 15:56.400
 So I've heard mention of Philip Roth's American Pastoral, which I love as a book.

15:56.400 --> 16:03.520
 I don't know if it was mentioned as something, I think, that was meaningful to you as well.

16:03.520 --> 16:07.440
 In either case, what literary books had a lasting impact on you?

16:07.440 --> 16:08.440
 What literature?

16:08.440 --> 16:09.800
 Yeah, okay, good question.

16:09.800 --> 16:17.800
 So I met Roth when we both got doctors from Harvard on the same day.

16:17.800 --> 16:18.800
 So we were...

16:18.800 --> 16:24.400
 Yeah, we had lunch together and stuff like that, but he knew that computer books would

16:24.400 --> 16:25.400
 never sell.

16:25.400 --> 16:36.160
 Well, all right, so you say you were a teenager when you left Russia, so I have to say that

16:36.160 --> 16:42.880
 Tolstoy was one of the big influences on me, especially like Anna Karnina.

16:42.880 --> 16:54.840
 Not because of the plot of the story, but because there's this character who...

16:54.840 --> 17:04.360
 The philosophical discussions, the whole way of life is worked out there among the characters,

17:04.360 --> 17:08.800
 and so that I thought was especially beautiful.

17:08.800 --> 17:15.720
 On the other hand, Dostoevsky, I didn't like it all because I felt that his genius was

17:15.720 --> 17:21.200
 mostly because he kept forgetting what he had started out to do and he was just sloppy.

17:21.200 --> 17:30.040
 I didn't think that he polished his stuff at all, and I tend to admire somebody who

17:30.040 --> 17:32.720
 dodged the eyes and crosses the T's.

17:32.720 --> 17:36.760
 So the music of the prose is what you admire more than...?

17:36.760 --> 17:41.680
 I certainly do admire the music of the language, which I couldn't appreciate in the Russian

17:41.680 --> 17:48.120
 original, but I can in Victor Hugo because French is closer.

17:48.120 --> 17:58.600
 But Tolstoy, the same reason I like Herman Wook as a novelist, I think his book Marjorie

17:58.600 --> 18:04.080
 Morningstar has a similar character in Hugo who developed his own personal philosophy

18:04.080 --> 18:08.760
 and it goes in the...

18:08.760 --> 18:09.760
 Was consistent?

18:09.760 --> 18:14.160
 Yeah, right, and it's worth pondering.

18:14.160 --> 18:18.200
 So you don't like Nietzsche and...

18:18.200 --> 18:19.200
 Like what?

18:19.200 --> 18:20.600
 You don't like Friedrich Nietzsche or...?

18:20.600 --> 18:28.080
 Nietzsche, yeah, no, no, yeah, I keep seeing quotations from Nietzsche and he never tempt

18:28.080 --> 18:29.800
 me to read any further.

18:29.800 --> 18:34.520
 Well, he's full of contradictions, so you will certainly not appreciate him.

18:34.520 --> 18:41.160
 But Schiller, I'm trying to get across what I appreciate in literature and part of it

18:41.160 --> 18:51.240
 is, as you say, the music of the language, the way it flows and take Raymond Chandler

18:51.240 --> 18:52.520
 versus Dashel Hammett.

18:52.520 --> 18:59.600
 Dashel Hammett's sentences are awful and Raymond Chandler's are beautiful, they just

18:59.600 --> 19:00.600
 flow.

19:00.600 --> 19:08.800
 So I don't read literature because it's supposed to be good for me or because somebody said

19:08.800 --> 19:17.440
 it's great, but I find things that I like, I mean, you mentioned you were dressed like

19:17.440 --> 19:24.040
 James Bond, so I love Ian Fleming, I think he's got a really great gift for...

19:24.040 --> 19:29.720
 If he has a golf game or a game of bridge or something and this comes into his story,

19:29.720 --> 19:38.000
 it'll be the most exciting golf game or the absolute best possible hands of bridge that

19:38.000 --> 19:45.800
 exists and he exploits it and tells it beautifully.

19:45.800 --> 19:54.160
 So in connecting some things here, looking at literate programming and being able to

19:54.160 --> 20:06.360
 convey encode algorithms to a computer in a way that mimics how humans speak, what do

20:06.360 --> 20:11.760
 you think about natural language in general and the messiness of our human world, about

20:11.760 --> 20:15.680
 trying to express difficult things?

20:15.680 --> 20:25.600
 So the idea of literate programming is really to try to understand something better by seeing

20:25.600 --> 20:30.920
 it from at least two perspectives, the formal and the informal, if we're trying to understand

20:30.920 --> 20:36.560
 the complicated thing, if we can look at it in different ways, and so this is in fact

20:36.560 --> 20:42.360
 the key to technical writing, a good technical writer trying not to be obvious about it but

20:42.360 --> 20:48.560
 says everything twice, formally and informally, or maybe three times, but you try to give

20:48.560 --> 20:57.800
 the reader a way to put the concept into his own brain or her own brain.

20:57.800 --> 21:01.920
 Is that better for the writer or the reader or both?

21:01.920 --> 21:09.040
 Well the writer just tries to understand the reader, that's the goal of a writer is to have

21:09.040 --> 21:18.120
 a good mental image of the reader and to say what the reader expects next and to impress

21:18.120 --> 21:24.760
 the reader with what has impressed the writer, why something is interesting.

21:24.760 --> 21:30.080
 So when you have a computer program, instead of looking at it as something that we're just

21:30.080 --> 21:35.520
 trying to give instruction to the computer, what we really want to be is giving insight

21:35.520 --> 21:43.520
 to the person who's going to be maintaining this program or to the programmer himself

21:43.520 --> 21:47.320
 when he's debugging it as to why this stuff is being done.

21:47.320 --> 21:54.200
 And so all the techniques of exposition that a teacher uses or a book writer uses make

21:54.200 --> 22:01.040
 you a better programmer if your program is going to be not just a one shot deal.

22:01.040 --> 22:04.680
 So how difficult is that?

22:04.680 --> 22:12.080
 Do you see hope for the combination of informal and formal for the programming task?

22:12.080 --> 22:18.240
 Yeah, I'm the wrong person to ask I guess because I'm a geek but I think for a geek

22:18.240 --> 22:19.240
 it's easy.

22:19.240 --> 22:29.240
 Well, I don't know, some people have difficulty writing and it might be because there's something

22:29.240 --> 22:34.400
 in their brain structure that makes it hard for them to write or it might be something

22:34.400 --> 22:36.520
 just that they haven't had enough practice.

22:36.520 --> 22:42.880
 I'm not the right one to judge but I don't think you can teach any person any particular

22:42.880 --> 22:43.880
 skill.

22:43.880 --> 22:51.800
 So I do think that that writing is half of my life and so I put it together in a litter

22:51.800 --> 22:52.800
 program.

22:52.800 --> 23:01.560
 Even when I'm writing a one shot program, I write it in a litter way because I get it

23:01.560 --> 23:04.800
 right faster that way.

23:04.800 --> 23:07.360
 Now does it get compiled automatically?

23:07.360 --> 23:08.360
 Or?

23:08.360 --> 23:15.840
 So I guess on the technical side my question was how difficult is a design, a system where

23:15.840 --> 23:20.120
 much of the programming is done informally?

23:20.120 --> 23:21.120
 Informally.

23:21.120 --> 23:22.120
 Yeah, informally.

23:22.120 --> 23:32.800
 I think whatever works to make it understandable is good but then you have to also understand

23:32.800 --> 23:33.800
 how informal it is.

23:33.800 --> 23:35.320
 You have to know the limitations.

23:35.320 --> 23:46.760
 So by putting the formal and informal together, this is where it gets locked into your brain.

23:46.760 --> 23:53.040
 You can say informally, well I'm working on a problem right now.

23:53.040 --> 23:54.760
 Let's go there.

23:54.760 --> 24:00.240
 Can you give me an example of connecting the informal and the formal?

24:00.240 --> 24:03.560
 Well, it's a little too complicated an example.

24:03.560 --> 24:13.520
 There's a puzzle that's called a Japanese arrow puzzle and you're given a bunch of boxes

24:13.520 --> 24:19.160
 each one points northeast, south or west and at the end you're supposed to fill in each

24:19.160 --> 24:25.120
 box with the number of distinct numbers that it points to.

24:25.120 --> 24:30.680
 So if I put a three in a box and it's pointing to five other boxes, that means that there's

24:30.680 --> 24:35.360
 going to be three different numbers in those five boxes.

24:35.360 --> 24:38.800
 And those boxes are pointing, one of them might be pointing to me, one of them might

24:38.800 --> 24:40.720
 be pointing the other way.

24:40.720 --> 24:48.680
 But anyway, I'm supposed to find a set of numbers that obeys this complicated condition

24:48.680 --> 24:55.240
 that each number counts how many distinct numbers it points to.

24:55.240 --> 25:04.680
 And so a guy sent me his solution to this problem where he presents formal statements

25:04.680 --> 25:10.880
 that say either this is true or this is true or this is true and so I try to render that

25:10.880 --> 25:20.760
 formal statement informally and I try to say I contain a three and the guys I'm pointing

25:20.760 --> 25:25.400
 to contain the numbers one, two and six.

25:25.400 --> 25:32.680
 So by putting it informally and also I convert it into a dialogue statement that helps me

25:32.680 --> 25:37.920
 understand the logical statement that he's written down as a string of numbers in terms

25:37.920 --> 25:41.200
 of some abstract variables that he had.

25:41.200 --> 25:42.200
 That's really interesting.

25:42.200 --> 25:45.560
 So maybe an extension of that.

25:45.560 --> 25:52.660
 There has been a resurgence in computer science and machine learning and neural networks.

25:52.660 --> 25:56.640
 So using data to construct algorithms.

25:56.640 --> 26:04.000
 So it's another way to construct algorithms really, if you can think of it that way.

26:04.000 --> 26:08.280
 So as opposed to natural language to construct algorithms use data to construct algorithms.

26:08.280 --> 26:15.800
 So what's your view of this branch of computer science where data is almost more important

26:15.800 --> 26:18.800
 than the mechanism of the algorithm?

26:18.800 --> 26:28.840
 It seems to be suited to a certain kind of nongeek and which is probably why it's taken

26:28.840 --> 26:34.800
 off that it has its own community that really resonates with that.

26:34.800 --> 26:42.720
 But it's hard to trust something like that because nobody, even the people who work with

26:42.720 --> 26:47.640
 it, they have no idea what has been learned.

26:47.640 --> 26:55.760
 That's a really interesting thought that it makes algorithms more accessible to a different

26:55.760 --> 26:59.720
 community, a different type of brain.

26:59.720 --> 27:07.360
 And that's really interesting because just like literate programming perhaps could make

27:07.360 --> 27:10.760
 programming more accessible to a certain kind of brain.

27:10.760 --> 27:15.480
 There are people who think it's just a matter of education and anybody can learn to be a

27:15.480 --> 27:23.600
 great programmer, anybody can learn to be a great skier.

27:23.600 --> 27:29.240
 I wish that were true, but I know that there's a lot of things that I've tried to do.

27:29.240 --> 27:35.000
 And I was well motivated and I kept trying to build myself up and I never got past a

27:35.000 --> 27:36.000
 certain level.

27:36.000 --> 27:44.120
 I can't view, for example, I can't view three dimensional objects in my head.

27:44.120 --> 27:48.560
 I have to make a model and look at it and study it from all points of view.

27:48.560 --> 27:55.000
 And then I start to get some idea of what other people are good at four dimensions.

27:55.000 --> 28:05.480
 Yeah, so let's go to the art of computer programming.

28:05.480 --> 28:13.920
 In 1962, you set the table of contents for this magnum opus, right?

28:13.920 --> 28:16.760
 It was supposed to be a single book with 12 chapters.

28:16.760 --> 28:26.840
 Now today, what is it, 57 years later, you're in the middle of volume 4 of 7.

28:26.840 --> 28:29.080
 In the middle of volume 4b is 4b.

