31:07.520 --> 31:09.600
 have to find stuff.

31:09.600 --> 31:16.800
 So again, algorithms that underlie all kinds of applications.

31:16.800 --> 31:20.680
 None of these volumes is about a particular application, but the applications are examples

31:20.680 --> 31:26.720
 of why people want to know about sorting, why people want to know about random numbers.

31:26.720 --> 31:31.080
 So then volume four goes into combinatorial algorithm.

31:31.080 --> 31:40.520
 This is where we have billions of things to deal with, and here, we keep finding cases

31:40.520 --> 31:48.360
 where one good idea can make something go more than a million times faster, and we're

31:48.360 --> 31:54.840
 dealing with problems that are probably never going to be solved efficiently, but that doesn't

31:54.840 --> 32:01.880
 mean we give up on them and we have this chance to have good ideas and go much, much faster

32:01.880 --> 32:02.880
 on them.

32:02.880 --> 32:08.080
 So that's combinatorial algorithms, and those are the ones that are, I mean, you said sorting

32:08.080 --> 32:09.240
 is most fun for you.

