 Well, it's true it's fun, but combinatorial algorithms are the ones that I always enjoyed

32:17.480 --> 32:23.160
 the most because that's when my skillet programming had the most payoff.

32:23.160 --> 32:31.640
 The difference between an obvious algorithm that you think of first thing and an interesting

32:31.640 --> 32:40.040
 subtle algorithm that's not so obvious but circles around the other one, that's where

32:40.040 --> 32:43.680
 computer science really comes in.

32:43.680 --> 32:50.200
 And a lot of these combinatorial methods were found first in applications to artificial

32:50.200 --> 32:59.920
 intelligence or cryptography, and in my case, I just liked them, and it was associated more

32:59.920 --> 33:00.920
 with puzzles.

33:00.920 --> 33:05.280
 Now, do you like the most in the domain of graphs and graph theory?

33:05.280 --> 33:11.600
 Graphs are great because they're terrific models of so many things in the real world,

33:11.600 --> 33:17.960
 and if you throw in numbers on a graph, you've got a network, and so there you have many

33:17.960 --> 33:20.180
 more things.

33:20.180 --> 33:30.080
 But combinatorial, in general, is any arrangement of objects that has some kind of a higher

33:30.080 --> 33:38.280
 structure, nonrandom structure, and is it possible to put something together satisfying

33:38.280 --> 33:43.960
 all these conditions, like I mentioned, arrows a minute ago, is there a way to put these

33:43.960 --> 33:48.040
 numbers on a bunch of boxes that are pointing to each other, is that going to be possible

33:48.040 --> 33:49.040
 at all?

33:49.040 --> 33:50.120
 That's volume four.

33:50.120 --> 33:51.120
 That's volume four.

33:51.120 --> 33:53.240
 What is the future hold?

33:53.240 --> 34:01.280
 Volume four A was part one, and what happened was, in 1962, when I started writing down

34:01.280 --> 34:07.360
 a table of contents, it wasn't going to be a book about computer programming in general,

34:07.360 --> 34:14.640
 it was going to be a book about how to write compilers, and I was asked to write a book

34:14.640 --> 34:22.480
 about how to write a compiler, and at that time, there were only a few dozen people in

34:22.480 --> 34:29.720
 the world who had written compilers, and I happen to be one of them, and I also had some

34:29.720 --> 34:38.600
 experience writing for the campus newspaper and things like that, so I said, okay, great,

34:38.600 --> 34:43.840
 I'm the only person I know who's written a compiler but hasn't invented any new techniques

34:43.840 --> 34:50.520
 for writing compilers, and all the other people I knew had super ideas, but I couldn't see

34:50.520 --> 34:55.040
 that they would be able to write a book that would describe anybody else's ideas but their

34:55.040 --> 35:02.600
 own, so I could be the journalist and I could explain what all these cool ideas about compiler

35:02.600 --> 35:10.280
 writing were, and then I started putting down, well, yeah, you need to have a chapter about

35:10.280 --> 35:15.000
 data structures, you need to have some introductory material, you want to talk about searching

35:15.000 --> 35:27.520
 because a compiler writer has to look up the variables in a symbol table and find out when

35:27.520 --> 35:31.880
 you write the name of a variable in one place, it's supposed to be the same as the one you

35:31.880 --> 35:38.880
 put somewhere else, so you need all these basic techniques, and I kind of know some

35:38.880 --> 35:44.480
 arithmetic and stuff, so I threw in these chapters, and I threw in a chapter on combinatorics

35:44.480 --> 35:49.520
 because that was what I really enjoyed programming the most, but there weren't many algorithms

35:49.520 --> 35:55.640
 in known about combinatorial methods in 1962, so that was kind of a short chapter, but it

35:55.640 --> 36:02.320
 was sort of thrown in just for fun, and chapter 12 was going to be actual compilers, applying

36:02.320 --> 36:08.240
 all the stuff in chapters 1 to 11 to make compilers, well, okay, so that was my table

36:08.240 --> 36:16.000
 of contents from 1962, and during the 70s, the whole field of combinatorics went through

36:16.000 --> 36:18.080
 a huge explosion.

36:18.080 --> 36:23.000
 People talk about a combinatorial explosion, and they usually mean by that, that the number

36:23.000 --> 36:29.680
 of cases goes up, you know, N plus 1, and all of a sudden your problem has gotten more

36:29.680 --> 36:37.920
 than 10 times harder, but there was an explosion of ideas about combinatorics in the 70s,

36:37.920 --> 36:45.800
 to the point that it takes 1975, I bet you more than half of all the journals of computer

36:45.800 --> 36:48.760
 science were about combinatorial methods.

36:48.760 --> 36:52.520
 What kind of problems were occupying people's minds?

36:52.520 --> 36:54.800
 What kind of problems in combinatorics?

36:54.800 --> 36:57.720
 Was it satisfiability, graph theory?

36:57.720 --> 37:06.840
 Yeah, graph theory was quite dominant, I mean, but all of the NP hard problems that you have

37:06.840 --> 37:13.600
 like, you know, Hamiltonian path, going beyond, yeah, going beyond graphs, you had operation

37:13.600 --> 37:19.480
 research, whenever there was a small class of problems that had efficient solutions,

37:19.480 --> 37:24.760
 and they were usually associated with matroid theory, special mathematical construction,

37:24.760 --> 37:31.040
 but once we went to things that involved three things at a time instead of two, all of a

37:31.040 --> 37:38.160
 sudden, things got harder, so we had satisfiability problems where if you have clauses, every

37:38.160 --> 37:43.200
 clause has two logical elements in it, then we can satisfy it in linear time.

37:43.200 --> 37:48.000
 We can test for satisfiability in linear time, but if you allow yourself three variables

37:48.000 --> 37:52.640
 in the clause, then nobody knows how to do it.

37:52.640 --> 37:59.880
 So these articles were about trying to find better ways to solve cryptography problems

37:59.880 --> 38:05.720
 than graph theory problems, where we have lots of data, but we didn't know how to find

38:05.720 --> 38:13.000
 the best subsets of the data, like with sorting, we could get the answer, didn't take long.

38:13.000 --> 38:16.480
 So how did it continue to change from the 70s to today?

38:16.480 --> 38:25.040
 Yeah, so now there may be half a dozen conferences whose topic is combinatorics, different kind,

38:25.040 --> 38:31.240
 but fortunately, I don't have to rewrite my book every month like I had to in the 70s.

38:31.240 --> 38:37.080
 But still, there's a huge amount of work being done, and people getting better ideas on these

38:37.080 --> 38:44.440
 problems that don't seem to have really efficient solutions, but we can still do a lot more

38:44.440 --> 38:45.440
 with them.

38:45.440 --> 38:51.440
 And so this book that I'm finishing now, I've got a whole bunch of brand new methods that

38:51.440 --> 39:00.560
 as far as I know, there's no other book that covers this particular approach.

39:00.560 --> 39:09.560
 And so I'm trying to do my best of exploring the tip of the iceberg, and I try out lots

39:09.560 --> 39:16.600
 of things and keep rewriting as I find better method.

39:16.600 --> 39:18.840
 So what's your writing process like?

39:18.840 --> 39:23.120
 What's your thinking and writing process like every day?

