 And I know a lot of people who, for whom baseball is the most important thing in the world.

47:46.920 --> 47:52.520
 But I also know a lot of people for whom cricket is the most important in the world or soccer

47:52.520 --> 47:55.040
 or something.

47:55.040 --> 47:59.760
 And I realized that if I had a big example, I mean, it was going to have a fold out illustration

47:59.760 --> 48:00.760
 and everything.

48:00.760 --> 48:05.880
 And I was saying, well, what am I really teaching about algorithms here where I had this baseball

48:05.880 --> 48:07.040
 example?

48:07.040 --> 48:12.560
 And if I was a person who knew only cricket, wouldn't they, what would they think about

48:12.560 --> 48:13.560
 this?

48:13.560 --> 48:19.040
 And so I've ripped the whole thing out, but I had something that would have really appealed

48:19.040 --> 48:23.880
 to people who grew up with baseball as a major theme in their life.

48:23.880 --> 48:29.160
 Which is a lot of people, but still a minority.

48:29.160 --> 48:30.160
 Small minority.

48:30.160 --> 48:33.480
 I took out bowling too.

48:33.480 --> 48:36.800
 Even a smaller minority.

48:36.800 --> 48:41.040
 What's the art in the art of programming?

48:41.040 --> 48:46.880
 Why is there, of the few words in the title, why is art one of them?

48:46.880 --> 48:52.080
 Well, that's what I wrote my touring lecture about.

48:52.080 --> 49:00.560
 And so when people talk about art, it really, I mean, what the word means is something that's

49:00.560 --> 49:02.560
 not in nature.

49:02.560 --> 49:09.760
 So when you have artificial intelligence, the art comes from the same root, saying that

49:09.760 --> 49:14.960
 this is something that was created by human beings.

49:14.960 --> 49:21.680
 And then it's gotten a further meaning of fine art, which has this beauty to the mix

49:21.680 --> 49:27.320
 and says, you know, we have things that are artistically done, and this means not only

49:27.320 --> 49:35.200
 done by humans, but also done in a way that's elegant and brings joy.

49:35.200 --> 49:49.000
 And has, I guess, Tolstoyber's Dostoevsky, but anyway, it's that part that says that

49:49.000 --> 49:54.120
 it's done well as well as not only different from nature.

49:54.120 --> 50:01.880
 In general, then, art is what human beings are specifically good at.

50:01.880 --> 50:07.440
 And when they say artificial intelligence, well, they're trying to mimic human beings.

50:07.440 --> 50:11.200
 But there's an element of fine art and beauty.

50:11.200 --> 50:12.200
 You are one.

50:12.200 --> 50:19.960
 And that's what I try to also say, that you can write a program and make a work of art.

50:19.960 --> 50:31.640
 So now, in terms of surprising, you know, what ideas in writing from sort and search

50:31.640 --> 50:40.480
 to the combinatorial algorithms, what ideas have you come across that were particularly

50:40.480 --> 50:48.240
 surprising to you, that changed the way you see a space of problems?

50:48.240 --> 50:52.640
 I get a surprise every time I have a bug in my program, obviously, but that isn't really

50:52.640 --> 50:53.640
 what you're at.

50:53.640 --> 50:57.200
 More transformational than surprising.

50:57.200 --> 51:03.400
 For example, in volume 4a, I was especially surprised when I learned about data structure

51:03.400 --> 51:15.080
 called BDD, Boolean Decision Diagram, because I sort of had the feeling that as an old timer,

51:15.080 --> 51:23.720
 and I've been programming since the 50s, and BDDs weren't invented until 1986.

51:23.720 --> 51:29.760
 And here comes a brand new idea that revolutionizes the way to represent a Boolean function.

51:29.760 --> 51:39.760
 Boolean functions are so basic to all kinds of things, I mean, logic underlies everything

51:39.760 --> 51:49.200
 we can describe, all of what we know in terms of logic somehow, and propositional logic.

51:49.200 --> 51:59.720
 I thought that was cut and dried and everything was known, but here comes Randy Bryant, and

51:59.720 --> 52:08.120
 he discovers that BDDs are incredibly powerful.

52:08.120 --> 52:14.320
 So that means I have a whole new section to the book that I never would have thought of

52:14.320 --> 52:26.400
 until 1986, not until 1990s, when people started to use it for a billion dollar of applications.

52:26.400 --> 52:32.840
 And it was the standard way to design computers for a long time until Satsalvers came along

52:32.840 --> 52:37.080
 in the year 2000, so that's another great big surprise.

52:37.080 --> 52:44.200
 So a lot of these things have totally changed the structure of my book, and the middle third

52:44.200 --> 52:56.040
 of volume 4b is about Satsalvers, and that's 300 plus pages, which is mostly about material

52:56.040 --> 52:59.480
 that was discovered in this century.

52:59.480 --> 53:07.000
 And I had to start from scratch and meet all the people in the field and write 15 different

53:07.000 --> 53:12.920
 Satsalvers that I wrote while preparing that, and seven of them are described in the book,

53:12.920 --> 53:16.160
 others were from my own experience.

53:16.160 --> 53:20.000
 So newly invented data structures or ways to represent?

53:20.000 --> 53:22.240
 A whole new class of algorithm.

53:22.240 --> 53:24.240
 A whole new class of algorithm.

53:24.240 --> 53:30.000
 Like the interesting thing about the BDDs was that the theoreticians started looking

53:30.000 --> 53:37.640
 at it and started to describe all the things you couldn't do with BDDs, and so they were

53:37.640 --> 53:48.200
 getting a bad name because they were useful, but they didn't solve every problem.

53:48.200 --> 53:54.360
 I'm sure that the theoreticians in the next 10 years are going to show why machine learning

53:54.360 --> 54:00.560
 doesn't solve everything, but I'm not only worried about the worst case, I get a huge

54:00.560 --> 54:05.600
 delight when I can actually solve a problem that I couldn't solve before, even though

54:05.600 --> 54:12.600
 I can't solve the problem that it suggests is a further problem, like I know that I'm

54:12.600 --> 54:14.160
 way better than I was before.

54:14.160 --> 54:20.040
 And so I found out that BDDs could do all kinds of miraculous things.

54:20.040 --> 54:31.080
 And so I had to spend quite a few years learning about that territory.

54:31.080 --> 54:38.600
 So in general, what brings you more pleasure, proving or showing a worst case analysis of

54:38.600 --> 54:46.520
 an algorithm or showing a good average case or just showing a good case, that something

54:46.520 --> 54:48.880
 good pragmatically can be done with this algorithm?

54:48.880 --> 54:54.640
 Yeah, I like a good case that is maybe only a million times faster than I was able to do

54:54.640 --> 55:03.000
 before, but not worry about the fact that it's still going to take too long if I double

55:03.000 --> 55:05.760
 the size of the problem.

55:05.760 --> 55:13.480
 So that said, you popularized the asymptotic notation for describing running time, obviously

55:13.480 --> 55:18.440
 in the analysis of algorithms, worst case is such an important part.

55:18.440 --> 55:26.080
 Do you see any aspects of that kind of analysis as lacking and notation too?

55:26.080 --> 55:33.200
 Well, the main purpose is to have notations that help us for the problems we want to solve.

55:33.200 --> 55:36.400
 And so that they match our intuitions.

55:36.400 --> 55:43.200
 And people who worked in number theory had used asymptotic notation in a certain way,

55:43.200 --> 55:46.760
 but it was only known to a small group of people.

55:46.760 --> 55:53.080
 And I realized that, in fact, it was very useful to be able to have a notation for something

55:53.080 --> 55:58.120
 that we don't know exactly what it is, but we only know partial about it and so on.

55:58.120 --> 56:05.440
 So for example, instead of big O notation, let's just take a much simpler notation where

56:05.440 --> 56:10.360
 I'd say zero or one or zero, one or two.

56:10.360 --> 56:16.520
 And suppose that when I had been in high school, we would be allowed to put in the middle of

56:16.520 --> 56:23.960
 our formula x plus zero, one or two equals y, okay?

56:23.960 --> 56:32.280
 And then we would learn how to multiply two such expressions together and deal with them.

56:32.280 --> 56:38.680
 Well, the same thing, big O notation says, here's something that I'm not sure what it

56:38.680 --> 56:44.120
 is, but I know it's not too big, I know it's not bigger than some constant times n squared

56:44.120 --> 56:45.120
 or something like that.

56:45.120 --> 56:47.480
 And so I write big O of n squared.

56:47.480 --> 56:52.240
 Now I learn how to add big O of n squared to big O of n cubed and I know how to add

56:52.240 --> 56:58.280
 big O of n squared to plus one and square that and how to take logarithms and exponentials

56:58.280 --> 57:00.760
 to have big O's in the middle of them.

57:00.760 --> 57:06.160
 And that turned out to be hugely valuable in all of the work that I was trying to do

57:06.160 --> 57:09.600
 is I'm trying to figure out how good an algorithm is.

57:09.600 --> 57:16.840
 So have there been algorithms in your journey that perform very differently in practice than

57:16.840 --> 57:18.320
 they do in theory?

57:18.320 --> 57:26.000
 Well, the worst case of a combinatorial algorithm is almost always horrible.

57:26.000 --> 57:32.880
 But we have SAT solvers that are solving one of the last exercises in that part of my book

57:32.880 --> 57:41.680
 was to figure out a problem that has a hundred variables that's difficult for a SAT solver.

57:41.680 --> 57:46.680
 But you would think that a problem with a hundred Boolean variables requires you to

57:46.680 --> 57:52.880
 do two to the one hundredth operations because that's the number of possibilities when you

57:52.880 --> 57:56.120
 have a hundred Boolean variables in two to the one hundredth.

57:56.120 --> 58:00.200
 Two to the one hundredth is way bigger than we can handle.

58:00.200 --> 58:03.560
 Ten to the seventeenth is a lot.

58:03.560 --> 58:08.620
 You've mentioned over the past few years that you believe P may be equal to NP.

58:08.620 --> 58:14.880
 But that is not really, you know, if somebody does prove that P equals NP, it will not directly

58:14.880 --> 58:20.080
 lead to an actual algorithm to solve difficult problems.

58:20.080 --> 58:21.680
 Can you explain your intuition here?

58:21.680 --> 58:23.680
 Has it been changed?

58:23.680 --> 58:28.320
 And in general, on the difference between easy and difficult problems of P and NP and so

58:28.320 --> 58:29.320
 on?

58:29.320 --> 58:30.320
 Yeah.

58:30.320 --> 58:38.800
 So the popular idea is if an algorithm exists, then somebody will find it.

58:38.800 --> 58:44.840
 And it's just a matter of writing it down.

58:44.840 --> 58:53.520
 But many more algorithms exist than anybody can understand or discover.

58:53.520 --> 59:01.560
 Because they're just way beyond human comprehension, the total number of algorithms is more than

59:01.560 --> 59:04.600
 mind boggling.

59:04.600 --> 59:10.440
 So we have situations now where we know that algorithm exists, but we don't know the

59:10.440 --> 59:13.760
 farthest idea what the algorithms are.

59:13.760 --> 59:24.360
 There are simple examples based on game playing where you say, well, there must be an algorithm

59:24.360 --> 59:29.640
 that exists to win in the game of Hex for the first player to win in the game of Hex

59:29.640 --> 59:35.080
 because Hex is always either a win for the first player or the second player.

59:35.080 --> 59:36.080
 But what's the game of Hex?

59:36.080 --> 59:42.720
 There's a game of Hex which is based on putting pebbles onto a hexagonal board and the white

59:42.720 --> 59:47.280
 player tries to get a white path from left to right and the black player tries to get

59:47.280 --> 59:49.760
 a black path from bottom to top.

59:49.760 --> 59:52.240
 And how does capture occur?

59:52.240 --> 59:53.240
 And there's no capture.

59:53.240 --> 59:56.280
 You just put pebbles down one at a time.

59:56.280 --> 1:00:00.320
 But there's no draws because after all the white and black are played, there's either

1:00:00.320 --> 1:00:05.840
 going to be a white path across from each to west or a black path from bottom to top.

1:00:05.840 --> 1:00:15.360
 So it's a perfect information game and people take turns like Tic Tac Toe.

1:00:15.360 --> 1:00:22.040
 And the hex board can be different sizes, but there's no possibility of a draw.

1:00:22.040 --> 1:00:24.640
 And players move one at a time.

1:00:24.640 --> 1:00:28.360
 And so it's got to be either a first player win or a second player win.

1:00:28.360 --> 1:00:34.360
 Mathematically, you follow out all the trees and either there's always a win for the first

1:00:34.360 --> 1:00:36.240
 player, second player, okay.

1:00:36.240 --> 1:00:37.240
 And it's finite.

1:00:37.240 --> 1:00:38.760
 The game is finite.

1:00:38.760 --> 1:00:41.640
 So there's an algorithm that will decide.

1:00:41.640 --> 1:00:45.920
 You can show it has to be one or the other because the second player could mimic the

1:00:45.920 --> 1:00:50.120
 first player with kind of a pairing strategy.

1:00:50.120 --> 1:00:56.600
 And so you can show that it has to be one or the other.

1:00:56.600 --> 1:00:58.800
 But we don't know any algorithm anyway.

1:00:58.800 --> 1:00:59.800
 We don't know.

1:00:59.800 --> 1:01:07.680
 There are cases where you can prove the existence of a solution, but nobody knows anyway how

1:01:07.680 --> 1:01:08.960
 to find it.

1:01:08.960 --> 1:01:15.480
 More like the algorithm question, there's a very powerful theorem in graph theory by

1:01:15.480 --> 1:01:24.200
 Robinson and Seymour that says that every class of graphs that is closed under taking

1:01:24.200 --> 1:01:31.560
 minors has a polynomial time algorithm to determine whether it's in this class or not.

1:01:31.560 --> 1:01:34.840
 Now a class of graphs, for example, planar graphs, these are graphs that you can draw

1:01:34.840 --> 1:01:38.680
 in a plane without crossing lines.

1:01:38.680 --> 1:01:46.040
 And the planar graph, taking minors means that you can shrink an edge into a point or

1:01:46.040 --> 1:01:49.320
 you can delete an edge.

1:01:49.320 --> 1:01:54.640
 And so you start with a planar graph and shrink any edge to a point, it's still planar.

1:01:54.640 --> 1:01:58.720
 Deleting an edge is still planar, okay.

1:01:58.720 --> 1:02:11.640
 But there are millions of different ways to describe a family of graphs that still remains

1:02:11.640 --> 1:02:14.280
 the same under taking minors.

1:02:14.280 --> 1:02:20.080
 And Robinson and Seymour proved that any such family of graphs, there's a finite number

1:02:20.080 --> 1:02:31.760
 of minimum graphs that are obstructions so that if it's not in the family, then it has

1:02:31.760 --> 1:02:37.880
 to contain, then there has to be a way to shrink it down until you get one of these

1:02:37.880 --> 1:02:41.840
 bad minimum graphs that's not in the family.

1:02:41.840 --> 1:02:47.160
 In the case of a planar graph, the minimum graph is a five point star where everything

1:02:47.160 --> 1:02:52.320
 points to another and the minimum graph consisting of trying to connect three utilities to three

1:02:52.320 --> 1:02:54.680
 houses without crossing lines.

1:02:54.680 --> 1:03:01.040
 And so there are two bad graphs that are not planar and every nonplanar graph contains

1:03:01.040 --> 1:03:07.040
 one of these two bad graphs by shrinking and removing edges.

1:03:07.040 --> 1:03:11.640
 Sorry, can you say that again so he proved that there's a finite number of these bad

1:03:11.640 --> 1:03:12.640
 graphs?

1:03:12.640 --> 1:03:13.640
 There's always a finite number.

1:03:13.640 --> 1:03:15.240
 So somebody says, here's a family of...

1:03:15.240 --> 1:03:17.720
 It's hard to believe.

1:03:17.720 --> 1:03:25.320
 And they proved the next sequence of 20 papers, I mean, and it's deep work, but it's...

1:03:25.320 --> 1:03:27.440
 Because that's for any arbitrary class.

1:03:27.440 --> 1:03:28.440
 So it's for any class.

1:03:28.440 --> 1:03:31.160
 Any arbitrary class that's closed under taking minors.

1:03:31.160 --> 1:03:32.640
 That's closed under...

1:03:32.640 --> 1:03:36.120
 Maybe I'm not understanding because it seems like a lot of them are closed under taking

1:03:36.120 --> 1:03:37.120
 minors.

1:03:37.120 --> 1:03:39.960
 Almost all the important classes of graphs are.

1:03:39.960 --> 1:03:48.040
 There are tons of such graphs, but also hundreds of them that arise in applications.

1:03:48.040 --> 1:03:52.960
 I have a book over here called Classes of Graphs.

1:03:52.960 --> 1:03:58.760
 And it's amazing how many different classes of graphs that people have looked at.

1:03:58.760 --> 1:04:02.600
 So why do you bring up this theorem, lower this proof?

1:04:02.600 --> 1:04:07.440
 So now there's lots of algorithms that are known for special class of graphs.

1:04:07.440 --> 1:04:13.760
 For example, if I have a chordal graph, then I can color it efficiently.

1:04:13.760 --> 1:04:18.800
 If I have some kinds of graphs, it'll make a great network of various things.

1:04:18.800 --> 1:04:22.000
 So you'd like to test...

1:04:22.000 --> 1:04:24.720
 Somebody gives you a graph that's always in this family of graphs.

1:04:24.720 --> 1:04:30.880
 If so, then I can go to the library and find an algorithm that's going to solve my problem

1:04:30.880 --> 1:04:33.160
 on that graph.

1:04:33.160 --> 1:04:34.160
 Okay.

1:04:34.160 --> 1:04:43.520
 So we want to have a graph that says, an algorithm that says, you give me a graph, I'll tell

1:04:43.520 --> 1:04:48.960
 you whether it's in this family or not.

1:04:48.960 --> 1:04:55.360
 And so all I have to do is test whether or not that does this given graph have a minor

1:04:55.360 --> 1:04:56.840
 that's one of the bad ones.

1:04:56.840 --> 1:05:01.880
 A minor is everything you can get by shrinking and removing it.

1:05:01.880 --> 1:05:06.160
 And given any minor, there's a polynomial time algorithm saying, I can tell whether

1:05:06.160 --> 1:05:09.720
 this is a minor of you.

1:05:09.720 --> 1:05:11.760
 And there's a finite number of bad cases.

1:05:11.760 --> 1:05:16.680
 So I just try, you know, does it have this bad case, polynomial time, I got the answer.

1:05:16.680 --> 1:05:23.480
 Does it have this bad case, polynomial time, I got the answer, total polynomial time.

1:05:23.480 --> 1:05:25.080
 And so I've solved the problem.

1:05:25.080 --> 1:05:28.680
 However, all we know is that the number of minors is finite.

1:05:28.680 --> 1:05:33.120
 We don't know what, we might only know one or two of those minors, but we don't know

1:05:33.120 --> 1:05:41.520
 that if we've got 20 of them, we don't know there might be 21, 25, all we know is that

1:05:41.520 --> 1:05:42.760
 it's finite.

1:05:42.760 --> 1:05:46.560
 So here we have a polynomial time algorithm that we don't know.

1:05:46.560 --> 1:05:51.760
 That's a really great example of what you worry about or why you think p equals NP won't

1:05:51.760 --> 1:06:00.200
 be useful, but still, why do you hold the intuition that p equals NP?

1:06:00.200 --> 1:06:12.080
 Because you have to rule out so many possible algorithms as being not working.

1:06:12.080 --> 1:06:18.440
 You can take the graph and you can represent it in terms of certain prime numbers and then

1:06:18.440 --> 1:06:28.400
 you can multiply those together and then you can take the bitwise and construct some certain

1:06:28.400 --> 1:06:33.440
 constant and polynomial time and that's a perfectly valid algorithm.

1:06:33.440 --> 1:06:45.160
 And there are so many algorithms of that kind, a lot of times we see random take data and

1:06:45.160 --> 1:06:56.400
 we get coincidences that some fairly random looking number actually is useful because it

1:06:56.400 --> 1:07:09.400
 happens to solve a problem just because there's so many hairs on your head, but it seems like

1:07:09.400 --> 1:07:15.280
 unlikely that two people are going to have the same number of hairs on their head.

1:07:15.280 --> 1:07:20.280
 But you can count how many people there are and how many hairs on their head.

1:07:20.280 --> 1:07:23.720
 So there must be people walking around in the country that have the same number of hairs

1:07:23.720 --> 1:07:24.720
 on their head.

1:07:24.720 --> 1:07:30.280
 Well, that's kind of a coincidence that you might say also this particular combination

1:07:30.280 --> 1:07:36.840
 of operations just happens to prove that a graph has a Hamiltonian path.

1:07:36.840 --> 1:07:43.400
 I see lots of cases where unexpected things happen when you have enough possibilities.

1:07:43.400 --> 1:07:48.080
 So because the space of possibility is so huge, your intuition just says it's not.

1:07:48.080 --> 1:07:52.360
 They have to rule them all out and so that's the reason for my intuition.

1:07:52.360 --> 1:07:53.360
 By no means approve.

1:07:53.360 --> 1:08:02.960
 I mean, some people say, well, P can't equal NP because you've had all these smart people.

1:08:02.960 --> 1:08:09.400
 The smartest designers of algorithms have been racking their brains for years and years

1:08:09.400 --> 1:08:16.320
 and there's a million dollar prizes out there and none of them, nobody has thought of algorithms.

1:08:16.320 --> 1:08:19.320
 So it must be no such algorithm.

1:08:19.320 --> 1:08:25.360
 On the other hand, I can use exactly the same logic and I can say, well, P must be equal

1:08:25.360 --> 1:08:28.640
 to NP because there are so many smart people out here that have been trying to prove it

1:08:28.640 --> 1:08:34.480
 unequal to NP and they've all failed.

1:08:34.480 --> 1:08:39.480
 This kind of reminds me of the discussion about the search for aliens that we've been

1:08:39.480 --> 1:08:44.040
 trying to look for them and we haven't found them yet therefore they don't exist, but

1:08:44.040 --> 1:08:50.520
 you can show that there's so many planets out there that they very possibly could exist.

1:08:50.520 --> 1:08:57.040
 Then there's also the possibility that they exist, but they all discovered machine learning

1:08:57.040 --> 1:09:01.160
 or something and then blew each other up.

1:09:01.160 --> 1:09:05.400
 On that small quick tangent, let me ask, do you think there's intelligent life out there

1:09:05.400 --> 1:09:06.960
 in the universe?

1:09:06.960 --> 1:09:08.400
 I have no idea.

1:09:08.400 --> 1:09:09.400
 Do you hope so?

1:09:09.400 --> 1:09:11.360
 Do you think about it?

1:09:11.360 --> 1:09:16.960
 I don't spend my time thinking about things that I could never know really.

1:09:16.960 --> 1:09:20.400
 And yet you do enjoy the fact that there's many things you don't know.

1:09:20.400 --> 1:09:23.720
 You do enjoy the mystery of things.

1:09:23.720 --> 1:09:33.200
 I enjoy the fact that I have limits, yeah, but I don't take time to answer unsolvable

1:09:33.200 --> 1:09:34.200
 questions.

1:09:34.200 --> 1:09:35.200
 Got it.

1:09:35.200 --> 1:09:40.560
 Well, because you've taken on some tough questions that may seem unsolvable.

1:09:40.560 --> 1:09:44.800
 You have taken on some tough questions that may seem unsolvable, but they're in the space.

1:09:44.800 --> 1:09:49.080
 It gives me a thrill when I can get further than I ever thought I could.

1:09:49.080 --> 1:09:50.840
 But I don't.

