 But much like with religion.

1:09:52.960 --> 1:09:58.560
 I'm glad that there's no proof that God exists or not.

1:09:58.560 --> 1:09:59.560
 I think...

1:09:59.560 --> 1:10:00.560
 It's spoiled the mystery.

1:10:00.560 --> 1:10:04.400
 It'll be too dull, yeah.

1:10:04.400 --> 1:10:14.640
 So to quickly talk about the other art of artificial intelligence, what's your view?

1:10:14.640 --> 1:10:18.520
 Artificial intelligence community has developed as part of computer science and in parallel

1:10:18.520 --> 1:10:21.640
 with computer science since the 60s.

1:10:21.640 --> 1:10:27.200
 What's your view of the AI community from the 60s to now?

1:10:27.200 --> 1:10:35.080
 So all the way through, it was the people who were inspired by trying to mimic intelligence

1:10:35.080 --> 1:10:40.680
 or to do things that were somehow the greatest achievements of intelligence that had been

1:10:40.680 --> 1:10:48.080
 inspiration to people who have pushed the envelope of computer science, maybe more than

1:10:48.080 --> 1:10:50.400
 any other group of people.

1:10:50.400 --> 1:11:01.240
 So all the way through, it's been a great source of good problems to sink teeth into

1:11:01.240 --> 1:11:10.680
 and getting partial answers and then more and more successful answers over the years.

1:11:10.680 --> 1:11:16.440
 So this has been the inspiration for lots of the great discoveries of computer science.

1:11:16.440 --> 1:11:23.200
 Are you yourself captivated by the possibility of creating, of algorithms having echoes of

1:11:23.200 --> 1:11:27.040
 intelligence in them?

1:11:27.040 --> 1:11:33.200
 Not as much as most of the people in the field, I guess I would say, but that's not to say

1:11:33.200 --> 1:11:39.920
 that they're wrong or that it's just you asked about my own personal preferences.

1:11:39.920 --> 1:11:52.480
 But the thing that I worry about is when people start believing that they've actually succeeded

1:11:52.480 --> 1:12:02.160
 and because there seems to be this huge gap between really understanding something and

1:12:02.160 --> 1:12:08.280
 being able to pretend to understand something and give the illusion of understanding something.

1:12:08.280 --> 1:12:11.360
 Everything is possible to create without understanding.

1:12:11.360 --> 1:12:12.360
 Yeah.

1:12:12.360 --> 1:12:24.160
 I do that all the time too, I mean, that's why I use random numbers, but there's still

1:12:24.160 --> 1:12:25.160
 this great gap.

1:12:25.160 --> 1:12:35.640
 I don't assert that it's impossible, but I don't see anything coming any closer to really

1:12:35.640 --> 1:12:38.440
 the kind of stuff that I would consider intelligence.

1:12:38.440 --> 1:12:45.080
 So you've mentioned something that on that line of thinking, which I very much agree

1:12:45.080 --> 1:12:46.080
 with.

1:12:46.080 --> 1:12:52.760
 So the art of computer programming as the book is focused on single processor algorithms

1:12:52.760 --> 1:12:57.720
 and for the most part, you mentioned...

1:12:57.720 --> 1:13:00.960
 That's only because I set the table of contents in 1962.

1:13:00.960 --> 1:13:01.960
 You have to remember.

1:13:01.960 --> 1:13:02.960
 For sure.

1:13:02.960 --> 1:13:03.960
 There's no...

1:13:03.960 --> 1:13:09.800
 I'm glad I didn't wait until 1965 or something.

1:13:09.800 --> 1:13:15.840
 One book, maybe we'll touch on the Bible, but one book can't always cover the entirety

1:13:15.840 --> 1:13:17.200
 of everything.

1:13:17.200 --> 1:13:26.240
 So I'm glad the table of contents for the art of computer programming is what it is.

1:13:26.240 --> 1:13:31.720
 But you did mention that you thought that understanding of the way ant colonies are

1:13:31.720 --> 1:13:37.760
 able to perform incredibly organized tasks might well be the key to understanding human

1:13:37.760 --> 1:13:38.760
 cognition.

1:13:38.760 --> 1:13:42.160
 So these fundamentally distributed systems.

1:13:42.160 --> 1:13:48.080
 So what do you think is the difference between the way Don Knuth would sort a list and an

1:13:48.080 --> 1:13:53.160
 ant colony would sort a list or perform an algorithm?

1:13:53.160 --> 1:13:58.160
 Sorting a list isn't the same as cognition though, but I know what you're getting at

1:13:58.160 --> 1:14:05.280
 there, so the advantage of ant colony, at least we can see what they're doing.

1:14:05.280 --> 1:14:13.680
 We know which ant has talked to which other ant and it's much harder with the brains to

1:14:13.680 --> 1:14:18.360
 know to what extent neurons are passing signal.

1:14:18.360 --> 1:14:21.800
 So I'm just saying that ant colony might be...

1:14:21.800 --> 1:14:29.720
 If they have the secret of cognition, think of an ant colony as a cognitive single being

1:14:29.720 --> 1:14:35.120
 rather than as a colony of lots of different ants, I mean just like the cells of our brain

1:14:35.120 --> 1:14:46.680
 are and the microbiome and all that is interacting entities, but somehow I consider myself to

1:14:46.680 --> 1:14:48.600
 be a single person.

1:14:48.600 --> 1:15:01.680
 So an ant colony, you can say, might be cognitive and somehow and I mean, okay, I smash a certain

1:15:01.680 --> 1:15:06.960
 ant and the organism thinks, hmm, that's stung, what was that?

1:15:06.960 --> 1:15:12.840
 But if we're going to crack the secret of cognition, it might be that we could do so

1:15:12.840 --> 1:15:20.440
 by psyching out how ants do it because we have a better chance to measure, they're communicating

1:15:20.440 --> 1:15:27.520
 by pheromones and by touching each other and psych, but not by much more subtle phenomenon

1:15:27.520 --> 1:15:30.400
 like current's going through.

1:15:30.400 --> 1:15:35.200
 But even a simpler version of that, what are your thoughts of maybe Conway's game of life?

1:15:35.200 --> 1:15:45.560
 Okay, so Conway's game of life is able to simulate any computable process and any deterministic

1:15:45.560 --> 1:15:46.560
 process is...

1:15:46.560 --> 1:15:47.880
 I like how you went there.

1:15:47.880 --> 1:15:56.840
 I mean, that's not its most powerful thing I would say, I mean, they can simulate it,

1:15:56.840 --> 1:16:03.880
 but the magic is that the individual units are distributed and extremely simple.

1:16:03.880 --> 1:16:06.960
 Yes, we understand exactly what the primitives are.

1:16:06.960 --> 1:16:09.680
 The primitives, just like with the ant colony, even simpler though.

1:16:09.680 --> 1:16:23.960
 But still, it doesn't say that I understand life, I mean, it gives me a better insight

1:16:23.960 --> 1:16:30.120
 into what does it mean to have a deterministic universe?

1:16:30.120 --> 1:16:34.920
 What does it mean to have free choice, for example?

1:16:34.920 --> 1:16:37.880
 So do you think God plays dice?

1:16:37.880 --> 1:16:38.880
 Yes.

1:16:38.880 --> 1:16:45.840
 I don't see any reason why God should be forbidden from using the most efficient ways to...

1:16:45.840 --> 1:16:54.800
 I mean, we know that dice are extremely important in efficient algorithms.

1:16:54.800 --> 1:16:58.920
 There are things that couldn't be done well without randomness, and so I don't see any

1:16:58.920 --> 1:17:03.880
 reason why God should be prohibited from...

1:17:03.880 --> 1:17:11.560
 When the algorithm requires it, you don't see why the physics should constrain it.

1:17:11.560 --> 1:17:17.120
 So in 2001, you gave a series of lectures at MIT about religion and science.

1:17:17.120 --> 1:17:19.440
 No, that was 1999.

1:17:19.440 --> 1:17:20.440
 You published...

1:17:20.440 --> 1:17:21.440
 Sorry.

1:17:21.440 --> 1:17:22.840
 The book came out in 2001.

1:17:22.840 --> 1:17:31.120
 So in 1999, you spent a little bit of time in Boston enough to give those lectures.

1:17:31.120 --> 1:17:36.360
 And I read in the 2001 version, most of it.

1:17:36.360 --> 1:17:37.360
 It's quite fascinating to read.

1:17:37.360 --> 1:17:40.920
 I recommend people, it's transcription review lectures.

1:17:40.920 --> 1:17:45.960
 So what did you learn about how ideas get started and grow from studying the history

1:17:45.960 --> 1:17:46.960
 of the Bible?

1:17:46.960 --> 1:17:52.400
 So you've rigorously studied a very particular part of the Bible.

1:17:52.400 --> 1:17:57.200
 What did you learn from this process about the way us human beings as a society develop

1:17:57.200 --> 1:18:01.560
 and grow ideas, share ideas, and define by those ideas?

1:18:01.560 --> 1:18:04.600
 Well, it's hard to summarize that.

1:18:04.600 --> 1:18:11.520
 I wouldn't say that I learned a great deal of really definite things where I could make

1:18:11.520 --> 1:18:15.000
 conclusions, but I learned more about what I don't know.

1:18:15.000 --> 1:18:21.800
 You have a complex subject which is really beyond human understanding.

1:18:21.800 --> 1:18:25.480
 So we give up on saying, I'm ever going to get to the end of the road and I'm ever going

1:18:25.480 --> 1:18:32.240
 to understand it, but you say, but maybe it might be good for me to get closer and closer

1:18:32.240 --> 1:18:34.520
 and learn more and more about something.

1:18:34.520 --> 1:18:39.480
 And so how can I do that efficiently?

1:18:39.480 --> 1:18:44.440
 And the answer is, well, use randomness.

1:18:44.440 --> 1:18:57.200
 And so try a random subset of that that is within my grasp and study that in detail instead

1:18:57.200 --> 1:19:04.320
 of just studying parts that somebody tells me to study or instead of studying nothing

1:19:04.320 --> 1:19:07.080
 because it's too hard.

1:19:07.080 --> 1:19:20.880
 So I decided for my own amusement once that I would take a subset of the verses of the

1:19:20.880 --> 1:19:30.000
 Bible and I would try to find out what the best thinkers have said about that small subset.

1:19:30.000 --> 1:19:36.680
 And I had about, let's say, 60 verses out of 3,000, I think is one out of 500 or something

1:19:36.680 --> 1:19:37.800
 like this.

1:19:37.800 --> 1:19:43.440
 And so then I went to the libraries, which are well indexed.

1:19:43.440 --> 1:19:52.400
 I spent, for example, at Boston Public Library, I would go once a week for a year.

1:19:52.400 --> 1:20:01.000
 And I went to have done timestuck and over Harvard Library to look at this book that

1:20:01.000 --> 1:20:08.400
 weren't in the Boston Public, where scholars had looked and you can go down the shelves

1:20:08.400 --> 1:20:15.480
 and you can look at the index and say, oh, is this verse mentioned anywhere in this book?

1:20:15.480 --> 1:20:17.680
 If so, look at page 105.

1:20:17.680 --> 1:20:22.520
 So in other words, I could learn not only about the Bible but about the secondary literature

1:20:22.520 --> 1:20:26.160
 about the Bible, the things that scholars have written about it.

1:20:26.160 --> 1:20:36.840
 And so that gave me a way to zoom in on parts of the things so that I could get more insight.

1:20:36.840 --> 1:20:44.760
 And so I look at it as a way of giving me some firm pegs, which I could hang pieces

1:20:44.760 --> 1:20:50.960
 of information but not as things where I would say, and therefore this is true.

1:20:50.960 --> 1:21:01.360
 In this random approach of sampling the Bible, what did you learn about the most, you know,

1:21:01.360 --> 1:21:05.920
 central, one of the biggest accumulation of ideas in our...

1:21:05.920 --> 1:21:13.320
 To me, that the main thrust was not the one that most people think of as saying, you know,

1:21:13.320 --> 1:21:16.280
 don't have sex or something like this.

1:21:16.280 --> 1:21:26.760
 But that the main thrust was to try to figure out how to live in harmony with God's wishes.

1:21:26.760 --> 1:21:32.280
 I'm assuming that God exists and as I say, I'm glad that there's no way to prove this

1:21:32.280 --> 1:21:43.840
 because I would run through the proof once and then I'd forget it and I would never speculate

1:21:43.840 --> 1:21:51.440
 about spiritual things and mysteries otherwise and I think my life would be very incomplete.

1:21:51.440 --> 1:22:02.200
 So I'm assuming that God exists, but a lot of the people say God doesn't exist but that's

1:22:02.200 --> 1:22:09.200
 still important to them and so in a way that might still be whether God is there or not.

1:22:09.200 --> 1:22:14.760
 In some sense, God is important to them.

1:22:14.760 --> 1:22:19.880
 One of the verses I studied, you can interpret it as saying, you know, it's much better

1:22:19.880 --> 1:22:25.040
 to be an atheist than not to care at all.

1:22:25.040 --> 1:22:29.960
 So I would say it's similar to the P equals NP discussion.

1:22:29.960 --> 1:22:37.080
 You mentioned a mental exercise that I'd love it if you could partake in yourself, a mental

1:22:37.080 --> 1:22:42.960
 exercise of being God and so how would you, if you were God, Dr. Nuth, how would you present

1:22:42.960 --> 1:22:45.280
 yourself to the people of earth?

1:22:45.280 --> 1:22:51.560
 You mentioned your love of literature and there's this book that really I can recommend

1:22:51.560 --> 1:22:52.560
 to you.

1:22:52.560 --> 1:22:55.800
 Yeah, the title I think is Blasphemy.

1:22:55.800 --> 1:23:08.200
 It talks about God revealing himself through a computer in Los Alamos and it's the only

1:23:08.200 --> 1:23:15.360
 book that I've ever read where the punchline was really the very last word of the book

1:23:15.360 --> 1:23:21.120
 and explained the whole idea of the book and so I don't want to give that away, but it's

1:23:21.120 --> 1:23:27.640
 really very much about this question that you raised.

1:23:27.640 --> 1:23:37.400
 But suppose God said, okay, my previous means of communication with the world are not the

1:23:37.400 --> 1:23:42.800
 best for the 21st century, so what should I do now?

1:23:42.800 --> 1:23:51.040
 And it's conceivable that God would choose the way that's described in this book.

1:23:51.040 --> 1:23:55.280
 And another way to look at this exercise is looking at the human mind, looking at the

1:23:55.280 --> 1:23:59.200
 human spirit, the human life in a systematic way.

1:23:59.200 --> 1:24:03.920
 I think it mostly, you want to learn humility, you want to realize that once we solve one

1:24:03.920 --> 1:24:10.600
 problem that doesn't mean that all of a sudden other problems are going to drop out and we

1:24:10.600 --> 1:24:22.160
 have to realize that there are things beyond our ability.

1:24:22.160 --> 1:24:25.560
 I see hubris all around.

1:24:25.560 --> 1:24:28.720
 Yeah, well said.

1:24:28.720 --> 1:24:36.200
 If you were to run program analysis on your own life, how did you do in terms of correctness,

1:24:36.200 --> 1:24:41.360
 spending time, resource use, asymptotically speaking, of course.

1:24:41.360 --> 1:24:42.360
 Okay, yeah.

1:24:42.360 --> 1:24:50.800
 Well, I would say that question has not been asked me before.

1:24:50.800 --> 1:25:07.440
 And I started out with library subroutines and learning how to be a automaton that was

1:25:07.440 --> 1:25:18.680
 obedient, and I had the great advantage that I didn't have anybody to blame for my failures

1:25:18.680 --> 1:25:24.320
 if I started getting, not understanding something, I knew that I should stop playing ping pong

1:25:24.320 --> 1:25:30.200
 and it was my fault that I wasn't studying hard enough or something, rather than that

1:25:30.200 --> 1:25:33.120
 somebody was discriminating against me in some way.

1:25:33.120 --> 1:25:40.920
 And I don't know how to avoid the existence of biases in the world, but I know that that's

1:25:40.920 --> 1:25:47.800
 an extra burden that I didn't have to suffer from.

1:25:47.800 --> 1:26:03.320
 Then I found the, from parents, I learned the idea of service to other people as being

1:26:03.320 --> 1:26:10.280
 more important than what I get out of stuff myself.

1:26:10.280 --> 1:26:21.280
 I know that I need to be happy enough in order to be able to be of service, but I came to

1:26:21.280 --> 1:26:29.400
 a philosophy finally that I phrase as point eight is enough.

1:26:29.400 --> 1:26:36.680
 There was a TV show once called Eight is Enough, which was about, somebody had eight kids.

1:26:36.680 --> 1:26:44.840
 But I say point eight is enough, which means if I can have a way of rating happiness, I

1:26:44.840 --> 1:26:56.280
 think it's good design to have an organism that's happy about 80% of the time.

1:26:56.280 --> 1:27:05.200
 And if it was 100% of the time, it would be like everybody's on drugs and everything

1:27:05.200 --> 1:27:09.440
 collapses and nothing works because everybody's just too happy.

1:27:09.440 --> 1:27:13.320
 Do you think you've achieved that point eight optimal balance?

1:27:13.320 --> 1:27:21.640
 There are times when I'm down and I know that I'm chemically, I know that I've actually

1:27:21.640 --> 1:27:28.400
 been programmed to be depressed a certain amount of time.

1:27:28.400 --> 1:27:33.440
 And if that gets out of kilter and I'm more depressed than usual, sometimes I find myself

1:27:33.440 --> 1:27:36.120
 trying to think, now, who should I be mad at today?

1:27:36.120 --> 1:27:43.920
 There must be a reason why I'm, but then I realize, it's just my chemistry telling

1:27:43.920 --> 1:27:48.160
 me that I'm supposed to be mad at somebody and so I truck it up and say, okay, go to

1:27:48.160 --> 1:27:56.600
 sleep and get better, but if I'm not 100% happy, that doesn't mean that I should find

1:27:56.600 --> 1:28:06.080
 somebody that's screaming and try to silence them, but I'm saying, okay, I'm not 100%

1:28:06.080 --> 1:28:15.360
 happy, but I'm happy enough to be a part of a sustainable situation.

1:28:15.360 --> 1:28:20.480
 So that's kind of the numerical analysis I do.

1:28:20.480 --> 1:28:25.520
 You've converged towards the optimal, which for human life is a point eight.

1:28:25.520 --> 1:28:32.680
 I hope it's okay to talk about, as you talked about previously in 2006, you were diagnosed

1:28:32.680 --> 1:28:34.800
 with prostate cancer.

1:28:34.800 --> 1:28:40.080
 Has that encounter with mortality changed you in some way or the way you see the world?

1:28:40.080 --> 1:28:41.760
 Well, yeah, it did.

1:28:41.760 --> 1:28:47.840
 The first encounter with mortality when my dad died and I went through a month when

1:28:47.840 --> 1:28:59.520
 I sort of came to be comfortable with the fact that I was going to die someday.

1:28:59.520 --> 1:29:12.400
 And during that month, I don't know, I felt okay, but I couldn't sing and I couldn't do

1:29:12.400 --> 1:29:19.320
 original research either, like I sort of remember after three or four weeks, the first time

1:29:19.320 --> 1:29:24.840
 I started having a technical thought that made sense and was maybe slightly creative.

1:29:24.840 --> 1:29:31.080
 I could sort of feel that something was starting to move again, but that was, you know, so

1:29:31.080 --> 1:29:39.920
 I felt very empty until I came to grips with the, I learned that this is sort of a standard

1:29:39.920 --> 1:29:42.520
 grief process that people go through.

1:29:42.520 --> 1:29:50.120
 Okay, so then now I'm at a point in my life, even more so than in 2006, where all of my

1:29:50.120 --> 1:29:58.600
 goals have been fulfilled except for finishing the art of computer programming.

1:29:58.600 --> 1:30:06.960
 I had one major unfulfilled goal that I'd wanted all my life to write a piece of music

1:30:06.960 --> 1:30:13.680
 that, and I had an idea for a certain kind of music that I thought ought to be written,

1:30:13.680 --> 1:30:20.120
 at least somebody ought to try to do it, and I felt that it wasn't going to be easy, but

1:30:20.120 --> 1:30:26.120
 I wanted it proof of concept, I wanted to know if it was going to work or not, and so

1:30:26.120 --> 1:30:33.960
 I spent a lot of time, and finally I finished that piece, and we had the world premiere

1:30:33.960 --> 1:30:38.480
 last year on my 80th birthday, and we had another premiere in Canada, and there's talk

1:30:38.480 --> 1:30:43.320
 of concerts in Europe and various things, so that, but that's done.

1:30:43.320 --> 1:30:49.120
 It's part of the world's music now, and it's either good or bad, but I did what I was hoping

1:30:49.120 --> 1:30:50.240
 to do.

1:30:50.240 --> 1:31:00.120
 So the only thing that I have on my agenda is to try to do as well as I can with the

1:31:00.120 --> 1:31:02.400
 art of computer programming until I go see now.

1:31:02.400 --> 1:31:06.920
 Do you think there's an element of 0.8 that might apply there?

1:31:06.920 --> 1:31:07.920
 0.8?

1:31:07.920 --> 1:31:08.920
 Yeah.

1:31:08.920 --> 1:31:24.360
 Well, I look at it more that I got actually to 1.0 when that concert was over with.

1:31:24.360 --> 1:31:31.760
 So in 2006 I was at 0.8, so when I was diagnosed with prostate cancer, then I said, okay, well

1:31:31.760 --> 1:31:39.560
 maybe this is, you know, I've had all kinds of good luck all my life, and I have nothing

1:31:39.560 --> 1:31:45.160
 to complain about, so I might die now, and we'll see what happens.

1:31:45.160 --> 1:31:58.080
 And so it's quite seriously, I had no expectation that I deserved better, I didn't make any

1:31:58.080 --> 1:31:59.720
 plans for the future.

1:31:59.720 --> 1:32:10.560
 I had my surgery, I came out of the surgery and spent some time learning how to walk again

1:32:10.560 --> 1:32:15.880
 and so on, it was painful for a while.

1:32:15.880 --> 1:32:21.160
 But I got home and I realized I hadn't really thought about what to do next.

1:32:21.160 --> 1:32:27.480
 I hadn't any expectations, I said, okay, hey, I'm still alive, okay, now I can write

1:32:27.480 --> 1:32:35.320
 some more books, but I didn't come with the attitude that, you know, this was terribly

1:32:35.320 --> 1:32:48.560
 unfair and I just said, okay, I was accepting whatever turned out, you know, I had gotten

1:32:48.560 --> 1:32:57.440
 more than my share already, so why should I, why should I, and I didn't, and I really

1:32:57.440 --> 1:33:01.800
 thought, when I got home, I realized that I had really not thought about the next step,

1:33:01.800 --> 1:33:07.440
 what I would do after I would be able to work again, I'd sort of thought of it as if this

1:33:07.440 --> 1:33:16.320
 might, you know, I was comfortable with the fact that it was at the end, but I was hoping

1:33:16.320 --> 1:33:28.320
 that I would still, you know, be able to learn about satisfiability and also someday even

1:33:28.320 --> 1:33:29.320
 write music.

1:33:29.320 --> 1:33:33.640
 I didn't start seriously on the music project until 2012.

1:33:33.640 --> 1:33:40.320
 So I'm going to be in huge trouble if I don't talk to you about this.

